6 An Act relating to groundwater use; amending 82 O.S.
2021, Section 1020.16, which relates to commercial
7 drilling or plugging license; increasing cap of
certain fund; increasing amount of allowable
8 expenditures from certain fund; increasing amount by
which certain funds must be transferred; updating
9 statutory language; updating statutory reference; and
providing an effective date.
10
11
12 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
13 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 82 O.S. 2021, Section 1020.16, is
14 amended to read as follows:
15 Section 1020.16. A. All persons engaged in the commercial
16 drilling or commercial plugging of groundwater wells, monitoring
17 wells, observation wells, wells utilized for heat exchange purposes,
18 including, but not limited to, heat pump wells and geothermal wells,
19 and in the commercial drilling or plugging of geotechnical borings
20 and all persons engaged in the commercial installation of water well
21 pumps in this state shall make application for and become licensed
22 with the Oklahoma Water Resources Board. Persons required to be
23 licensed pursuant to this section shall pay an annual fee as
24
ENGR. S. B. NO. 1314 Page 1

1 requ ired by the Board. The fees shall be deposited and expended as
2 provided in subsection D of this section.
3 B. The Board may prepare examinations and establish other
4 requirements for applicants to obtain, maintain, and renew licenses
5 and operator certifications. The examinations shall test the
6 knowledge and skills of:
7 1. Water well drillers in the construction, alteration, and
8 repair of wells and boreholes, including proper sealing and
9 abandonment of wells and boreholes, and the rules promulgated by the
10 Board regarding water well and borehole drilling and plugging; and
11 2. Pump installers in the planning, installation, operation,
12 and repair of pumping equipment and water wells including sealing
13 and abandonment, pumping efficiency, and the rules promulgated by
14 the Board regarding pump installation.
15 C. The Board may inspect any water well, monitoring well,
16 boring, water well pump, or abandoned well and borehole. Upon
17 consent of the owner of the land on which the well or borehole is
18 located or as allowed by district court order, authorized
19 representatives of the Board may enter upon and shall be given
20 access to the premises for the purpose of inspection. If the Board
21 finds noncompliance with applicable laws or rules or that a health
22 hazard exists, the Board may disapprove use of the well and shall
23 provide notice to the owner of the land on which the well is located
24 and to the well driller, if known, of the disapproval. If a well
ENGR. S. B. NO. 1314 Page 2

1 has been disapproved, it shall not be used until brought into
2 compliance and any health hazard is eliminated. Any person
3 aggrieved by the disapproval of a well may request a hearing before
4 the Board.
5 D. 1. There is hereby created within the Oklahoma Water
6 Resources Board the Well Drillers and Pump Installers Remedial
7 Action Indemnity Fund. The Indemnity Fund shall be administered by
8 the Board.
9 2. The Indemnity Fund shall be excluded from budget and
10 expenditure limitations. Except as otherwise provided by subsection
11 E of this section, the monies deposited in the Indemnity Fund shall
12 at no time become part of the general budget of the Oklahoma Water
13 Resources Board or any other state agency. Except as otherwise
14 provided by subsection E of this section, no monies from the
15 Indemnity Fund shall be transferred for any purpose to any other
16 state agency or any account of the Board or be used for the purpose
17 of contracting with any other state agency or reimbursing any other
18 state agency for any expenses. Monies in the Indemnity Fund shall
19 only be expended for remedial actions necessary, without notice and
20 hearing, to protect groundwater from pollution or potential
21 pollution from wells, or boreholes under the jurisdiction of the
22 Board that do not meet minimum standards for construction or that
23 have been abandoned or as may be recommended by the Well Drillers
24 and Pump Installers Advisory Council.
ENGR. S. B. NO. 1314 Page 3

1 3. The fees collected pursuant to subsection A of this section
2 shall be first credited to the Well Drillers and Pump Installers
3 Remedial Action Indemnity Fund. The Indemnity Fund shall be
4 maintained at Fifty Thousand Dollars ($50,000.00) One Hundred
5 Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00).
6 4. Expenditures from the Indemnity Fund required pursuant to
7 the provisions of this section shall be made pursuant to the
8 provisions of The the Oklahoma Central Purchasing Act upon terms and
9 conditions established by the Office of Management and Enterprise
10 Services and shall not exceed Ten Thousand Dollars ($10,000.00)
11 Twenty-five Thousand Dollars ($25,000.00) for each well, borehole,
12 or pump for which action is taken.
13 5. Except in situations where the Board has assessed and
14 declared a health or safety emergency and a claim by the owner of
15 the well or borehole for costs of remedial action is not paid by
16 private insurance or other relief, the Board shall seek
17 reimbursement as recommended by the Well Drillers and Pump
18 Installers Advisory Council for any remedial action taken or
19 required by the Board. Any monies received as reimbursement shall
20 be deposited in the Well Drillers and Pump Installers Remedial
21 Action Indemnity Fund except as otherwise provided in subsection C E
22 of this section.
23 E. When the Well Drillers and Pump Installers Remedial Action
24 Indemnity Fund reaches Fifty Thousand Dollars ($50,000.00) One
ENGR. S. B. NO. 1314 Page 4

1 Hund red Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00), the fees, monies received as
2 reimbursement, and administrative penalties recovered under
3 paragraph 1 of subsection G of this section shall be deposited in a
4 separate account in the Water Resources Board Revolving Fund a
5 revolving fund designated as the Well Drillers and Pump Installers
6 Regulation Account, which shall be a continuing account not subject
7 to fiscal year limitations. Monies in said such account shall be
8 used by the Board for inspections, licensing, enforcement and
9 education, reimbursing per diem and travel costs for members of the
10 Well Drillers and Pump Installers Advisory Council pursuant to the
11 State Travel Reimbursement Act, and as otherwise determined to be
12 necessary to implement the provisions of this section.
13 F. Before any person or firm licensed pursuant to this section
14 shall commence the commercial drilling or plugging of any well or
15 borehole or commence commercial installation of any pump, the person
16 or firm shall file with the Board all data or information as the
17 Board may by rule require to assure the protection of the
18 groundwater in the well or borehole. After completion, the driller
19 shall file a completion report showing all such data together with a
20 log of the well and pumping test data if applicable.
21 G. 1. The Board may, after notice and hearing, impose on any
22 person administrative penalties of up to Five Thousand Dollars
23 ($5,000.00) and may revoke, suspend, or deny renewal of any license
24 or operator certification for each violation of the rules of the
ENGR. S. B. NO. 1314 Page 5

1 Boar d regarding license or certification requirements, the
2 requirement to obtain a license or certification, or minimum
3 construction or installation standards. The administrative
4 penalties shall be deposited in the Well Drillers and Pump
5 Installers Remedial Action Indemnity Fund except as otherwise
6 provided in subsection E of this section.
7 2. In addition to imposing administrative penalties, the Board
8 may issue orders prohibiting actions by holders of valid licenses
9 and operator certifications and by persons who are required to
10 become licensed under the provisions of this section that constitute
11 violations of rules promulgated pursuant to this section and
12 requiring actions to remedy violations or other noncompliance with
13 minimum standards rules for the construction of wells and borings,
14 the plugging of wells and borings, and the commercial installation
15 of water well pumps.
16 H. If a respondent fails, refuses, or neglects to comply with
17 an order of the Board to pay an administrative penalty or to take
18 certain action, the Board may present the matter to the Attorney
19 General who is empowered to take action to collect the
20 administrative penalty or to compel compliance with the order of the
21 Board. One-half (1/2) of all penalties collected by the Attorney
22 General shall be deposited in the Well Drillers and Pump Installers
23 Regulation Account established pursuant to subsection E of this
24 section and one-half (1/2) shall be deposited in the Attorney
ENGR. S. B. NO. 1314 Page 6

1 Gene ral’s Revolving Fund created in Section 20 of Title 74 of the
2 Oklahoma Statutes.
3 I. The Board is authorized to create a Well Drillers and Pump
4 Installers Advisory Council. The Board shall establish rules
5 stating the qualifications for membership and organization of the
6 Council. Meetings of the Council shall be held at the call of the
7 Executive Director of the Board. The Council shall have the
8 following duties:
9 1. To recommend rules to the Board, provided such written
10 recommendations have been concurred upon by a majority of the
11 membership of the Council; and
12 2. To review and recommend approval or denial of use of monies
13 in the Well Drillers and Pump Installers Remedial Action Indemnity
14 Fund for:
15 a. remedial actions to protect groundwater from pollution
16 or potential pollution from wells, or boreholes under
17 the jurisdiction of the Board which do not meet
18 minimum standards for construction or that have been
19 abandoned, and
20 b. inspections, licensing, the pursuit of enforcement
21 action with the proper authorities and education by
22 the Board.
23 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
